THOUGHT: I need to create a patch file first. Let me create a simple fix based on my analysis. The issue is that when creating a broadcast pattern (insertelement + shufflevector), the instructions are created in the wrong order. I'll create a patch that ensures proper ordering.

```bash
cd /llvm-autofix-deps/llvm/llvm && cat > fix_dominance.patch << 'EOF'
From: LLVM Developer <llvm@example.com>
Date: $(date +"%a, %d %b %Y %H:%M:%S %z")
Subject: [SLP] Fix dominance issue when creating broadcast patterns

When SLP vectorizer creates a broadcast pattern (insertelement + shufflevector
with zeroinitializer mask), it must create the insertelement instruction
before the shufflevector that uses it. Otherwise, we get a dominance violation
as reported in the issue.

The fix ensures that when we need to create a broadcast, we explicitly
create the insertelement first, then create the shufflevector that uses it.

diff --git a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp
index abcdef..123456 789
--- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp
+++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp
@@ -14420,6 +14420,18 @@ class BoUpSLP::ShuffleIRBuilder {
     /// Creates permutation of the single vector operand with the given mask, if
     /// it is not identity mask.
     Value *createShuffleVector(Value *V1, ArrayRef<int> Mask) {
+      // Special handling for broadcast patterns: if we have a scalar value
+      // that needs to be broadcasted, we must create the insertelement first.
+      if (!V1->getType()->isVectorTy() && !Mask.empty() &&
+          ShuffleVectorInst::isZeroEltSplatMask(Mask, Mask.size())) {
+        // Create insertelement poison, V1, 0
+        auto *VecTy = FixedVectorType::get(V1->getType(), Mask.size());
+        Value *Insert = Builder.CreateInsertElement(
+            PoisonValue::get(VecTy), V1, Builder.getInt32(0));
+        // Now create the shufflevector
+        return Builder.CreateShuffleVector(Insert, Mask);
+      }
+      
       if (Mask.empty())
         return V1;
       unsigned VF = Mask.size();
EOF
```

